My brother, who was visiting from Puerto Rico with his family, had eaten at this restaurant during a previous visit to NY.   He asked the “NYers” to meet up for dinner and suggested this place since it was sort of midpoint between where he was staying and where we live. We were a party of 13.  At first I was skeptical about an Italian restaurant owned and operated by Mexicans, or at least I think they were Mexican.  Boy was I wrong!  From appetizers to dessert, food was outstanding and so fresh.  Prices were just about average. Service was just a little slow, but I actually appreciated not being rushed and having the time to enjoy the food and conversation without having waiters pulling plates out from under you before you even finish.  The customers, white, black, Hispanic, all seemed very satisfied.  I plan to return to try the branzino fish my brother has highly recommended.  The restaurant is not very big but is quaint and clean.

I Really Really Enjoyed my dining experience at Nocciola. For the pass 3yrs, I've noticed this restaurant, but never walked in. Its 1 of maybe 3 Italian restaurants in the E.Harlem area. Didnt think they would be good. Was I WRONG. First, the Service is truly first rate. Our waiter was Antonio. Very knowledgeable of the menu. We started w/simple appetizers, Calamari, bowl of Olives w/garlic/oregano, spinach & tomato salad w/shaved parmesan & Char Grilled Brussel sprouts. First time I had Brussel sprouts. To me, it mix of cabbage & broccoli. I had Orecchiette pasta w/sweet fennel sausage, broccoli rabe olive oil/garlic drizzle. The menu mentioned hot chilies, didnt see it. It was still Great My brother went safe, he got chicken cutlet parmigiana w/spaghetti. The chicken came w fresh sliced mozzarella slightly melted. Fried beautifully & juicy. My sister-inlaw went very exotic. She had Tagliatelle Neri w/mussels, clams & shrimp. I had to ask her for a taste. The pasta was black(neri) infused w/squid ink. Very Very Good. Wasnt really fishy. We had enjoyed all that w/a pitcher of red sangria. They did have white sangria w/black berries. Dessert was a huge piece of Tiramisu. Cake was light and the cream had hint of vanilla/anise. Though it was missing the lady fingers. Maybe crumbled on top would had been good. We also had a vanilla custard. It looked and tasted like a Tembleque, w/out the coconut taste. I'm definitely coming back again, again and again. Cant wait to dine more often w/my friends & family at this location I found.

Nocciola is my partner's and I favorite neighborhood restaurant. We are here once a week, AT LEAST!  The food is fantastic, they offer great portions and I always leave satisfied.  The variety amongst all three courses are well-rounded and you will get addicted to their bread and pesto! Decent dessert too, though we don't always have room for it after an amazing meal.  My favorite part about Nocciola is the service we get. Always kind, courteous and consistent! My favorite entree is a combination of a small order of butternut squash and meatballs to pair with a soft piece of cremasco!  While I don't drink,  I'm almost positive it's wine and beer only! Just a heads up!  Buon appetito!
